AGI - After seven years Emmanuel&nbsp;Macron>, he returns to the historic Parisian University of the Sorbonne where, in 2017, as a young president just elected, he had launched his programmatic speech for Europe and imposed himself as leader on the community scene. Today, a few weeks after the European elections, the Elysian tenant tries again, in a different capacity and context, and with two wars that upset the balances of the world, launches his new political manifesto: "Europe can die," he must become a military power and think more about growth." Attacked by external enemies, centred on the borders of his Continent, marred internally by the opposition of Rassemblement National, which directs the electoral victory,&nbsp;Macron&nbsp; wears the warrior's clothes and proposes a new vision of his European doctrine. "Europe is encircled and is not armed enough," said citing the challenges posed by "unscrupulous regional authorities" such as China and Russia. "The rules of the game have changed," he continued, and it ended the time when the United States was a saving anchor. "In the next decade, there is an immense risk of being weakened," he added, "we must be aware that our Europe can die, and this depends solely on our choices, which must be accomplished now because it is today that our ability to guarantee our security is at stake."
&nbsp;
And it is therefore France that goes down to the field and that is put into play in all its 'grandmother'. "The French army is ready to put itself at the forefront of European defence thanks also to the atomic weapon, an indispensable element of European defence to build security guarantees" of the Continent, said the French President. Strong words, he decided that this time I also liked the German ally Olaf Scholz, less convinced when the transalpine ally had ventilated NATO's involvement in the war in Ukraine: "Good impulses - it was the comment to the Berlin leader's speech - because Europe remains strong." And to stay strong, Europe must exploit its most powerful military options. "France has the nuclear weapon, therefore, the possibility of dissuasion" said&nbsp; Macron, "the nuclear weapon is an indispensable element of European defence to build the security guarantees that our partners in Europe expect." So the call to partners to "not be more vassals than the U.S." and to "produce more weapons and faster." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Not only war, economic competitiveness is a priority. In the face of the appetite of external powers, such as China and Russia, Emmanuel&nbsp;Macron&nbsp; called for a revival of the economy to avoid the risk that Europe is in a "stall". Hence the call to the BCE not to think too much about inflation but more about growth, to review the models of the continent no longer "sustainable", to avoid "impoverishment". "We cannot have demanding environmental and social standards, invest less than our competitors and think that we will continue to create jobs. He no longer holds up" he warned by pointing his finger at countries that do not submit themselves to the "economic game rules", China and the US. "The two main international powers have decided not to respect trade rules anymore," he added. "We rule too much, we invest too little, > we are too open and we do not defend enough our interests."
&nbsp;
That is why Europe must consider a "revision" of its commercial policy.> "We will invent a continent which overly binds its producers on its territory and which, through its commercial policy, eliminates constraints for others," he insisted. Finally, the political attack on the 'nationalists' and the 'anti-European' who, he said, "they stay in the European palace without paying rent or respecting the rules of compromise", an attitude that could lead Europe to "love" if Europeanists let themselves be won by "timidity". "All European nationalisms no longer dare to say that they will come out of the euro and Europe. But we were all used to a "yes" speech, which is, "I will put in my pocket everything that Europe has done but I will do it not respecting the rules," said the French president ending his speech at the Sorbonne. "The risk is that all others become shy in saying that nationalists, anti-Europeans are very strong everywhere," while the answer to fears is "audacity." &nbsp;
